<article>
    <h1>Sur&#xAD;pris&#xAD;ing Fac&#xAD;tors That Could Lead To Type 2 Di&#xAD;a&#xAD;betes</h1>
    <h2>Other than un&#xAD;healthy weight range and fam&#xAD;ily his&#xAD;tory, shift work, sit&#xAD;ting for too long and skip&#xAD;ping break&#xAD;fast could also in&#xAD;crease your risk of de&#xAD;vel&#xAD;op&#xAD;ing the con&#xAD;di&#xAD;tion</h2>
    <section>
        <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/textview" title="The Straits Times">The Straits Times</a>
        - <a href="/singapore/the-straits-times/20201113/textview" title="The Straits Times - 2020-11-13"><time>2020-11-13</time></a>
        - <span>LIFE</span>
        - <span role="byline"></span>
    </section>

    <p>Ear­lier this year, Se­nior Par­lia­men­tary Sec­re­tary for Health Am­rin Amin said in Par­lia­ment that about 19,000 peo­ple are di­ag­nosed with Type 1 or Type 2 di­a­betes each year.</p>
    <p>He added that there are many ex­ist­ing ini­tia­tives aimed at re­duc­ing the risk of de­vel­op­ing di­a­betes and de­lay­ing the on­set of com­pli­ca­tions in those who al­ready have the dis­ease. But it will take years be­fore both the over­all in­ci­dence of di­a­betes and its com­pli­ca­tion rate de­crease.</p>
    <p>Ac­cord­ing t o t he lat­est avail­able Na­tional Pop­u­la­tion Health Sur­vey, 8.6 per cent of Sin­ga­pore res­i­dents had di­a­betes in 2017.</p>
    <p>Link be­tween di­a­betes and blood sugar levels</p>
    <p>Di­a­betes oc­curs when the body’s blood sugar levels stay above nor­mal on a con­sis­tent ba­sis, mak­ing it dif­fi­cult for the body to turn food into en­ergy.</p>
    <p>There are two types of di­a­betes. Type 1 is ge­netic and un­pre­ventable; it oc­curs be­cause the pan­creas does not nat­u­rally pro­duce enough i nsulin, a hor­mone that con­trols blood glu­cose l evels. It i s com­mon among chil­dren, t eenagers and young adults.</p>
    <p>Type 2 di­a­betes is the most com­mon form of di­a­betes and is re­lated to weight man­age­ment. Risk fac­tors as­so­ci­ated with this in­clude un­healthy weight range, age, fam­ily his­tory, lack of ex­er­cise and a his­tory of ges­ta­tional di­a­betes.</p>
    <p>A change i n diet, good life­style habits and keep­ing within a healthy weight range could sig­nif­i­cantly lower your risk of de­vel­op­ing Type 2 di­a­betes. How­ever, there are some lesser-known fac­tors that could in­crease your risk.</p>
    <p>Shift work</p>
    <p>The Har­vard School of Public Health found that women who work three or more night shifts per month are at risk of de­vel­op­ing Type 2 di­a­betes. Those who work a ro­tat­ing night shift for three or more years face a 20 per cent in­creased risk and af­ter 10 years or more, there’s a 40 per cent in­creased risk. That’s be­cause shift work in­creases cor­ti­sol — or stress hor­mone — pro­duc­tion, which pre­dis­poses peo­ple to di­a­betes.</p>
    <p>Skip­ping break­fast</p>
    <p>Miss­ing the first meal of the day dis­rupts in­sulin pro­duc­tion and in­creases waist cir­cum­fer­ence, which boosts di­a­betes risk. The risk also in­creases be­cause you’re more likely to eat un­healthy foods later in the day.</p>
    <p>Sit­ting for too long</p>
    <p>Re­searchers at the Baker IDI Heart and Di­a­betes In­sti­tute in Mel­bourne are in­ves­ti­gat­ing how the num­ber of hours we spend sit­ting at work could im­pact our di­a­betes risk. It seems a loss of mus­cle con­trac­tion when sit­ting may im­pair the body’s abil­ity to clear glu­cose and fat from the blood.</p>
    <p>Drink­ing juice</p>
    <p>A study of 70,000 women by Tu­lane Uni­ver­sity in New Orleans found those who drank 180ml or a glass of fruit juice a day had an 18 per cent in­creased risk of di­a­betes. Fruit juice sug­ars are ab­sorbed quickly and this causes a rapid spike in blood sugar levels, whereas fruit eaten as a whole is di­gested slowly. Try switch­ing to plain wa­ter in­stead.</p>
    <p>A lack of sleep</p>
    <p>Not get­ting enough sleep raises stress and in­creases levels of the hor­mone cor­ti­sol. Too much cor­ti­sol is linked to a dys­func­tion of the pan­creas cells that pro­duce in­sulin, so the in­sulin you make doesn’t work as well.</p>
    <p>This ar­ti­cle was first pub­lished in The Sin­ga­pore Women’s Weekly.</p>

